-- Hong Kong shares slip on profit-taking, poor earnings
-- By Grace Li
-- Wed Aug 27, 2014 04:11AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, Aug 27 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares finished lower on Wednesday, hit by afternoon session losses as investors took profit on recent outperformers and sold shares in companies with weak earnings.

The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> ended 0.6 percent lower at a nearly two-week closing low of 24,918.75 points. The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the leading offshore Chinese listings in Hong Kong was down 0.5 percent, snapping a three-day winning streak. Asia insurance giant AIA Group <1299.HK>, which reached a record high on Monday, lost 1.2 percent. Sinopec Corp <0386.HK> was pulled down a further 1.3 percent from its 6-1/2-year high also hit on Monday. Guangzhou Automobile Group <2238.HK> sank 5.7 percent after its first-half earnings report on Tuesday failed to show positive growth prospects for the company. That was the same with Want Want China <0151.HK>, which slid 2.1 percent to a two-month low.